00:33:42,079 --> 00:33:43,559
Don't worry.

484
00:33:44,601 --> 00:33:46,556
I'm gonna kill somebody.

485
00:33:52,842 --> 00:33:54,434
Better call Brikowski.

486
00:33:54,522 --> 00:33:56,080
Tell him there's a new face in town.

487
00:34:32,409 --> 00:34:34,286
- Hey.
- Nick still hasn't shown, huh?

488
00:34:34,369 --> 00:34:36,201
- No.
- What's with you and that towel?

489
00:34:36,290 --> 00:34:37,847
Oh... Lindsey...

490
00:34:38,610 --> 00:34:42,000
- It's a very long story.
- Get dressed, and tell me about it on the way.

491
00:34:42,090 --> 00:34:43,365
Where are we going?

492
00:34:43,451 --> 00:34:46,284
All we know is that somebody called Nick
from the Hotel Cheval.

493
00:34:46,371 --> 00:34:48,328
<i>I spoke to a friend who works there.</i>

494
00:34:48,411 --> 00:34:50,368
<i>They keep a record of every call made.</i>

495
00:34:50,452 --> 00:34:54,730
<i>She can access the computer and we can</i>
<i>find out what room the call came from.</i>

496
00:34:54,813 --> 00:34:56,451
What is it?

497
00:34:56,533 --> 00:34:58,490
- I know this guy.
<i>- Who?</i>

498
00:34:58,573 --> 00:34:59,972
This guy.

499
00:35:01,374 --> 00:35:03,330
You know that guy?

500
00:35:03,414 --> 00:35:05,326
Yeah, I met him.

501
00:35:05,415 --> 00:35:06,768
He was dead.

502
00:35:09,216 --> 00:35:11,172
You met a dead guy?

503
00:35:11,256 --> 00:35:13,212
Yeah.

504
00:35:13,296 --> 00:35:15,253
In a walk-in freezer.

505
00:35:18,777 --> 00:35:21,850
Bookmaker Slim Hopkins reported missing.
Police have no leads.

506
00:35:21,937 --> 00:35:23,496
Blah, blah, blah. Yada, yada...

507
00:35:23,578 --> 00:35:27,458
A spokesperson commented off the record,
"Ironic that Hopkins should go missing,

508
00:35:27,539 --> 00:35:32,169
considering he's allegedly been behind
a few disappearing acts himself."

509
00:35:35,180 --> 00:35:39,332
I think it's time you told me that story
about why you're still wearing that towel.

510
00:35:39,421 --> 00:35:41,776
- Do you mind if I get dressed first?
- (Phone rings)

511
00:35:41,861 --> 00:35:44,501
Could be my friend from the hotel. Be right back.

512
00:35:47,982 --> 00:35:49,540
Hm.

513
00:36:00,104 --> 00:36:03,415
Hey, Lindsey, I don't think it's such a good idea
that we continue to...

514
00:36:05,266 --> 00:36:07,541
Put your shoes on, Schlomo wants to see you.

515
00:36:11,106 --> 00:36:13,063
I don't know anyone named Schlomo.

516
00:36:14,107 --> 00:36:17,578
Someone named Schlomo knows you.
That is your only concern.

517
00:36:17,668 --> 00:36:19,021
Let's go.

518
00:36:19,108 --> 00:36:20,861
Like I said, I don't know...

519
00:36:22,669 --> 00:36:24,625
Aaahh... better...

520
00:36:25,629 --> 00:36:28,190
I think it's better if you let me do the talking.

521
00:36:28,269 --> 00:36:29,703
You think?

522
00:36:35,591 --> 00:36:38,105
What is it?

523
00:36:40,152 --> 00:36:41,505
He's sorry that he hit you.

524
00:36:41,592 --> 00:36:43,549
- Do you always speak for him?
- <i>Yes.</i>

525
00:36:45,633 --> 00:36:47,305
Hm.

526
00:36:47,394 --> 00:36:49,350
So, he's a mute, then.

527
00:36:49,433 --> 00:36:50,389
Not quite.

528
00:36:50,474 --> 00:36:52,430
Well, what, then?

529
00:36:52,514 --> 00:36:54,982
It's personal. You'll have to ask him.

530
00:36:55,075 --> 00:36:57,031
- Hm. How would he tell me?
- He wouldn't.

531
00:37:01,836 --> 00:37:03,747
- Hey, are we going to the...?
- No.

532
00:37:03,836 --> 00:37:06,146
- But he's right there.
- A different outfit entirely.

533
00:37:07,597 --> 00:37:09,475
<i>Right across the street from one another?</i>

534
00:37:09,557 --> 00:37:13,710
At one time they were one with one another.
And then they tried to kill one another.

535
00:37:14,798 --> 00:37:19,236
<i>And now neither man leaves</i>
<i>his respective tower of isolation</i>

536
00:37:19,319 --> 00:37:21,674
for fear of what the other man will do to him.

537
00:37:30,561 --> 00:37:32,517
Let me guess, all the way up?

538
00:37:35,282 --> 00:37:37,238
Penthouse.

539
00:37:44,404 --> 00:37:46,360
Gentle piano music

540
00:38:04,767 --> 00:38:06,917
You must be Mr. Fisher.

541
00:38:09,408 --> 00:38:12,320
Must I? Because... that hasn't been
working out for me lately.

542
00:38:12,409 --> 00:38:15,048
- But I'm afraid you must.
- Well, if I must.

543
00:38:16,250 --> 00:38:18,605
Do you know for what reason
you've been brought here?

544
00:38:22,291 --> 00:38:23,883
For starters, I'm unlucky.

545
00:38:23,971 --> 00:38:27,805
The unlucky are nothing more than
a frame of reference for the lucky, Mr. Fisher.

546
00:38:27,891 --> 00:38:30,645
You are unlucky so I may know that I am not.

547
00:38:30,732 --> 00:38:34,168
Unfortunately, the lucky never realize
they are lucky until it's too late.

548
00:38:34,253 --> 00:38:37,723
Take yourself for instance. Yesterday
you were better off than you are today,

549
00:38:37,814 --> 00:38:42,968
but it took today for you to realize it. But...
today has arrived, and it's too late, you see?

550
00:38:44,415 --> 00:38:46,326
<i>People are never happy with what they have.</i>

551
00:38:47,415 --> 00:38:50,725
They always want what they had,
or what someone else has.

552
00:38:50,815 --> 00:38:53,125
Kinda like a rabbi
who would rather be a gangster,

553
00:38:53,216 --> 00:38:55,127
a gangster who would rather be a rabbi.

554
00:38:55,216 --> 00:38:56,251
I mean, what is that?

555
00:38:56,337 --> 00:38:59,409
Some sort of grass is always greener
on the other side of the fence thing?

556
00:38:59,498 --> 00:39:02,649
<i>I mean, how do you justify being a rabbi</i>

557
00:39:02,738 --> 00:39:04,808
and a gangster?

558
00:39:08,619 --> 00:39:10,291
I don't.

559
00:39:10,379 --> 00:39:13,337
I'm a bad man who doesn't waste time
wondering what could've been,

560
00:39:13,420 --> 00:39:15,411
when I am what could've been or not have been.

561
00:39:15,500 --> 00:39:19,130
I live on both sides of the fence,
and my grass is always green.

562
00:39:19,781 --> 00:39:21,737
Consider, Mr. Fisher...

563
00:39:22,421 --> 00:39:24,252
...there are two men sitting here before you,

564
00:39:24,341 --> 00:39:27,220
and one of them you should be very afraid of.
Where's my money?

565
00:39:28,503 --> 00:39:31,222
- I've been hearing that a lot lately.
- My father used to say,

566
00:39:31,303 --> 00:39:33,897
"The first time somebody calls you a horse,
you punch him.

567
00:39:33,984 --> 00:39:36,623
The second time somebody calls you a horse,
call him a jerk.

568
00:39:36,703 --> 00:39:40,823
But the third time somebody calls you a horse,
perhaps it's time to go shopping for a saddle."

569
00:39:50,106 --> 00:39:53,782
- I don't have your money.
- This isn't like skipping out on the check.

570
00:39:53,866 --> 00:39:57,143
You owe me money.
I have interests, you owe them money.

571
00:39:57,228 --> 00:40:00,026
- I don't even know how much money I owe you.
- $33,000.

572
00:40:00,108 --> 00:40:02,417
- But I'm not Nick fisher.
- Then who the hell are you?

573
00:40:02,508 --> 00:40:05,660
I'm just a guy who was in the wrong place
at the wrong time.

574
00:40:08,910 --> 00:40:10,866
You have 48 hours to get my money.

575
00:40:10,950 --> 00:40:14,182
Saul will keep an eye on you.
In the meantime, you may go now.

576
00:40:20,192 --> 00:40:21,545
Wait, I just have one question.

577
00:40:23,112 --> 00:40:25,069
I wasn't frisked.

578
00:40:30,434 --> 00:40:34,313
I see. So, being a rabbi, a... a religious man...

579
00:40:34,395 --> 00:40:38,593
There are three things a Jew may not do
in order to save a life, including his own.

580
00:40:38,675 --> 00:40:44,433
He may not idol-worship, commit adultery,
or perform an act of premeditated murder.

581
00:40:45,156 --> 00:40:47,465
Killing you before you killed me
would have been...

582
00:40:47,556 --> 00:40:49,513
- Kosher.
- (Exhales)

583
00:40:52,558 --> 00:40:53,513
Acceptable.

584
00:41:12,641 --> 00:41:14,996
I've wired half the money
to your bank in the Caymans.

585
00:41:15,082 --> 00:41:18,200
The other half will be deposited
when our old friend is in the ground.

586
00:41:18,282 --> 00:41:20,239
Now I can expect that when?

587
00:41:24,763 --> 00:41:26,799
- Very soon.
- Good.

588
00:41:26,884 --> 00:41:29,478
So, tell me. The kid...

589
00:41:30,284 --> 00:41:32,241
<i>What do you want with him?</i>

590
00:41:34,325 --> 00:41:36,475
The kid and I have unfinished business.

591
00:41:46,007 --> 00:41:48,727
If there's one thing I know,
it's when someone is lying.

592
00:41:48,807 --> 00:41:50,959
A man in my position, it's all he has to go on.

593
00:41:52,448 --> 00:41:55,919
To know a lie when he hears it,
it's the difference between life and death -

594
00:41:56,009 --> 00:41:57,681
your own, someone else's.

595
00:41:57,770 --> 00:42:00,728
That being said, he wasn't lying.

596
00:42:01,890 --> 00:42:03,243
That's not Nick Fisher.

597
00:42:04,371 --> 00:42:05,405
I know.

598
00:42:15,773 --> 00:42:20,086
I came back here, you were gone. So,
I went to the hotel without you to see my friend.

599
00:42:20,174 --> 00:42:23,007
She says the call to Nick came from Room 1009.

600
00:42:23,094 --> 00:42:26,724
A fellow registered under the name of Smith,
if you can believe that.

601
00:42:26,814 --> 00:42:30,525
It's one of the most common names in the world,
so there's bound to be a couple of 'em.

602
00:42:30,615 --> 00:42:32,811
But I get the feeling that this ain't one of 'em.

603
00:42:32,895 --> 00:42:35,808
I get up to the tenth floor, and just as I do,

604
00:42:35,896 --> 00:42:39,651
the door to room 1009 opens
and there's our Mr. Smith. In the flesh.

605
00:42:39,737 --> 00:42:44,448
So, I pretend I'm walking to the elevator instead
of coming from it and we take it down together.

606
00:42:44,538 --> 00:42:46,574
He smiles at me - thanks - I smile back.

607
00:42:47,499 --> 00:42:49,888
<i>But I have no idea who he is</i>
<i>but I think you might,</i>

608
00:42:49,979 --> 00:42:53,176
<i>so I take a picture using my cell phone</i>
<i>which I thought was a total waste</i>

609
00:42:53,260 --> 00:42:55,694
cos the photos look like shit and I never use it.

610
00:42:55,780 --> 00:43:00,730
So there I am pretending to dial a number,
and taking Smith's picture - him none the wiser.

611
00:43:01,581 --> 00:43:03,651
This is Smith. Recognize him?

612
00:43:03,741 --> 00:43:04,491
No.

613
00:43:05,382 --> 00:43:09,898
I didn't think you would, but it was worth a shot.
Anyway, we take the elevator to the lobby,

614
00:43:09,982 --> 00:43:13,692
and the man who calls himself Smith
walks outside and hails himself a cab.

615
00:43:13,783 --> 00:43:15,535
So I followed him.

616
00:43:21,025 --> 00:43:24,017
<i>He went down</i>
<i>into an apartment building downtown.</i>

617
00:43:24,105 --> 00:43:26,175
<i>So I wait. An hour goes by.</i>

618
00:43:27,425 --> 00:43:30,463
And just when I'm getting ready to leave -
who walks outside?

619
00:43:30,546 --> 00:43:32,298
- Smith?
- You.

620
00:43:36,707 --> 00:43:37,457
Me?

621
00:43:39,347 --> 00:43:43,307
<i>You out of the same building</i>
<i>with two Hasidic Jews on either side of you.</i>

622
00:43:44,268 --> 00:43:46,100
Friends of yours?

623
00:43:47,109 --> 00:43:48,508
Not exactly.

624
00:43:48,590 --> 00:43:50,740
I think it's time you told me that story.

625
00:43:52,150 --> 00:43:55,188
Well, there's this guy
and they call him The Boss, right?

626
00:43:56,231 --> 00:43:59,507
And then, right across the street
there's this man they call The Rabbi.

627
00:43:59,592 --> 00:44:02,629
- Why do they call him The Rabbi?
- Because he's a rabbi.

628
00:44:10,113 --> 00:44:13,026
So now I have to "take out",
to use the vernacular,

629
00:44:13,114 --> 00:44:15,913
The Fairy, in order to scratch a debt
that isn't even mine.

630
00:44:15,994 --> 00:44:21,592
And if that's not enough, I have 48 hours to
come up with $33,000 or The Rabbi's gonna...

631
00:44:22,556 --> 00:44:24,512
I don't know who Mr. Smith is.

632
00:44:25,396 --> 00:44:28,230
And the worst part about it is,
I'm not Nick Fisher.

633
00:44:28,997 --> 00:44:29,747
Ironic.

634
00:44:30,757 --> 00:44:32,396
I know, I don't even gamble.

635
00:44:32,477 --> 00:44:35,514
No, I mean the mobster having a gay son.
That's ironic.

636
00:44:38,319 --> 00:44:41,117
We are dealing with a bona fide case
of mistaken identity here.

637
00:44:41,199 --> 00:44:44,908
Things like that aren't supposed to be real.
It's like amnesia.

638
00:44:44,999 --> 00:44:49,118
Notwithstanding, here you are,
and Nick's nowhere to be found, so...

639
00:44:49,200 --> 00:44:51,396
I'd say you're fucked.

640
00:44:51,481 --> 00:44:53,392
Fucked.

641
00:44:56,842 --> 00:44:58,958
Shouldn't you be a little worried about this?

642
00:44:59,043 --> 00:45:01,238
I have Ataraxia.

643
00:45:01,322 --> 00:45:02,472
Ataraxia?

644
00:45:03,563 --> 00:45:08,592
It's a condition characterized by freedom
from worry or any other preoccupation really.

645
00:45:10,845 --> 00:45:13,074
I have to have my answer
to The Boss in the morning.

646
00:45:13,164 --> 00:45:15,121
Oh, what are you gonna say?

647
00:45:16,445 --> 00:45:19,039
What a man with two penises would say
when his tailor asks him

648
00:45:19,126 --> 00:45:21,594
- if he dresses to the right or to the left.
- What's that?

649
00:45:24,167 --> 00:45:25,043
Yes.

650
00:45:25,967 --> 00:45:27,923
I knew you had sense.

651
00:45:29,487 --> 00:45:32,241
Sense is something you have
when you have a choice.

652
00:45:32,328 --> 00:45:34,080
Sometimes.

653
00:45:34,168 --> 00:45:36,524
Sometimes it's when you know you don't.

654
00:45:37,969 --> 00:45:41,405
Nah, don't move that bishop!
It's an obvious sucker bet.

655
00:45:42,170 --> 00:45:44,638
If you don't, y-y-you can have him in four moves.

656
00:45:44,730 --> 00:45:47,040
If you do, he's gonna have you in mate in one.

657
00:45:49,931 --> 00:45:51,445
He doesn't see it.

658
00:45:51,532 --> 00:45:54,092
Wouldn't matter if he did.

659
00:45:54,172 --> 00:45:55,606
Elvis lets me win.

660
00:45:56,773 --> 00:45:58,809
<i>Everybody lets me win.</i>

661
00:45:59,573 --> 00:46:02,406
Wait a minute. You know this game?

662
00:46:09,495 --> 00:46:11,167
THE BOSS: You got three days.

663
00:46:12,895 --> 00:46:14,614
I was thinking it would take me a week.

664
00:46:14,695 --> 00:46:17,085
Oh, you were thinking that, were you?

665
00:46:17,177 --> 00:46:21,216
With all your experience killing people?
I'll tell you what.

666
00:46:23,297 --> 00:46:25,208
You win this game, you got your week.

667
00:46:29,618 --> 00:46:30,256
Hm.

668
00:46:40,380 --> 00:46:43,179
THE BOSS: So, what's the plan with Yitzchok?

669
00:46:44,581 --> 00:46:46,300
Was gonna play it by ear.

670
00:46:46,381 --> 00:46:49,419
Well, if it's all the same,
I'd write it down. It's a tough tune.

671
00:46:50,902 --> 00:46:52,894
And, by the way, he has shadows.

672
00:46:56,583 --> 00:46:58,336
Shadows?

673
00:47:02,265 --> 00:47:03,936
Bodyguards.

674
00:47:04,664 --> 00:47:06,621
With him all the time.

675
00:47:08,426 --> 00:47:10,223
Military.

676
00:47:15,106 --> 00:47:17,063
Ex-Israeli Mossad.

677
00:47:18,467 --> 00:47:22,347
THE BOSS: They go where he goes,
round-the-clock. Ex-Israeli Mossad.

678
00:47:22,428 --> 00:47:24,384
Ex-Israeli Mossad.

679
00:47:26,909 --> 00:47:28,058
That doesn't sound good.

680
00:47:29,229 --> 00:47:31,379
<i>They live in the apartment next door.</i>

681
00:47:32,269 --> 00:47:34,466
He wears a panic button on a chain
around his neck.

682
00:47:34,550 --> 00:47:36,587
<i>Looks like an ordinary Star of David.</i>

683
00:47:37,431 --> 00:47:40,662
He presses that button
and, well, we all know how that ends.

684
00:47:40,751 --> 00:47:42,104
What's this?

685
00:47:43,232 --> 00:47:44,300
Oh, God! No, you didn't?

686
00:47:47,273 --> 00:47:48,945
- Get down!
- (Silenced gunshot)

687
00:47:50,593 --> 00:47:52,789
<i>Response time's gonna be</i>
<i>three to five seconds.</i>

688
00:47:53,514 --> 00:47:55,709
He's gonna have to hit him
when he least expects it.

689
00:47:55,794 --> 00:47:57,750
Where?

690
00:47:57,834 --> 00:48:00,554
- Where?
- The apartment.

691
00:48:01,875 --> 00:48:05,470
How do I get in his apartment?
I can't just walk in the front door.

692
00:48:06,196 --> 00:48:08,471
No, I was thinking you'd use the back door.

693
00:48:15,718 --> 00:48:17,709
Then what?

694
00:48:17,798 --> 00:48:19,948
He does the kid, I do him.

695
00:48:20,839 --> 00:48:23,307
I plant my gun. Clean, no history.

696
00:48:23,399 --> 00:48:27,393
And Yitzchok - fire a round,
get some powder burns on the hands.

697
00:48:28,720 --> 00:48:32,270
Take the clothes off- make it look like a,

698
00:48:32,361 --> 00:48:36,878
"You do me, I do you, we're both gay, the
world doesn't understand us," double suicide.

699
00:48:38,162 --> 00:48:39,914
And that's all there is to it.

700
00:48:41,002 --> 00:48:43,072
Is that all there is to it?

701
00:48:43,163 --> 00:48:45,552
Yeah. It's all there is to it.

702
00:48:53,964 --> 00:48:55,034
Peww!

703
00:48:57,925 --> 00:48:59,962
I'm not such a bad guy, you know.

704
00:49:01,606 --> 00:49:03,756
<i>Some folks have grown pretty fat off me.</i>

705
00:49:06,407 --> 00:49:08,363
Some have grown pretty dead.

706
00:49:12,768 --> 00:49:14,167
You're a conundrum, you.

707
00:49:16,409 --> 00:49:20,846
You walk in here shooting your fucking mouth off
like you don't give a fuck if it gets shot off.

708
00:49:22,090 --> 00:49:23,443
You can only kill me once.

709
00:49:31,131 --> 00:49:31,882
Checkmate.

710
00:49:38,133 --> 00:49:40,089
Nobody says I have to kill you quick.

711
00:49:43,334 --> 00:49:45,086
Cat.

712
00:49:46,134 --> 00:49:47,886
Mouse.

713
00:49:49,495 --> 00:49:51,451
You've got three days.

714
00:49:55,255 --> 00:49:57,212
Excuse me.

715
00:50:17,179 --> 00:50:18,738
Who the fuck is this guy?

716
00:50:19,700 --> 00:50:23,011
<i>Dunno. But whoever he is, he's either in</i>
<i>very deep shit or I don't know what,</i>

717
00:50:23,100 --> 00:50:27,777
because he's playing in the sandbox with
